  <body>
    <div rend="parallel">
      <lg xml:id="ITA36">
<l>ciṟiyār perumai ciṟitiṉka ṇeytu</l>
<l>maṟiyārun tāmaṟiyā rāva – raṟiyāmai</l>
<l>maṇkoṇṭu maṇṇuṇṭu maṇṇumiḻnta māyaṉeṉ</l>
<l>ṟeṇkoṇṭeṉ ṉeñcē yiru</l>
      </lg>
      <lg xml:lang="en">
<l>All the ignorant ones</l>
<l>who attain in what is little the greatness of little ones,</l>
<l>			they are ignorant ones. Without knowing<note xml:lang="en" place="foot">Here the negative verbal noun aṟiyāmai is used in the function of a negative absolutive, as occasionally happens in a transitional phase represented, for example, by the Tiṇaimālai Nūṟṟaimpatu 114.2 cintāmai, but see also Pē. 94.4 poṉṟāmai.</note> think:<note xml:lang="en" place="foot">eṇ-koṇṭu: koḷ is employed here as the reflexive auxiliary: thinking for one’s own sake.</note></l>
<l>‘the Dark one who has taken, eaten [and] spit out the world,’</l>
<l>my heart, [and] stick [to it].</l>
      </lg>
    </div>
  </body>
